This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL) because it focuses on detecting changes between word frequency tables and applies the method to authorship attribution. It also mentions identifying discriminating words, which is a common task in computational linguistics. 

The paper could also belong to the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category because authorship attribution is a task related to information retrieval. 

The machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category is also a possibility because the paper mentions that the method performs well without handcrafting and tuning, which suggests the use of machine learning techniques. 

The artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category is another possibility because the paper uses a statistical test to identify changes between word frequency tables, which is a common task in artificial intelligence. 

Finally, the computer science and game theory (cs.CC) sub-category is a less likely possibility because the paper does not explicitly mention game theory, but the Higher Criticism test has been used in game theory research.
